description.narrative: Frontline health and community workers have improved capacity to provide quality, essential maternal and neonatal care (including PMTCT and CMR) to pregnant women/girls and babies in emergency and non-emergency settings.,which contributes to Hiv Prevention, Maternal And Newborn Health. title.narrative: Frontline health and community workers have improved capacity to provide quality, essential maternal and neonatal care (including PMTCT and CMR) to pregnant women/girls and babies in emergency and non-emergency settings.

description.narrative: Forty per cent of UNICEF-supported basic emergency obstetric and newborn care health facilities (25 out of 63) were operational on a 24/7 basis (target 24 per cent); and 14% of health facilities (57 out of 378 prevention of mother-to-child transmission of HIV [PMTCT] sites at national level) were supported to provide PMTCT services and lifelong antiretroviral treatment for pregnant and breastfeeding women (target 20%). A total of 1,056 (616 males and 440 females) frontline and community health workers had their skills enhanced and were better equipped to provide quality care through training in maternal and/or newborn care. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:31/12/2019
